  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Wintering at Changsu Station in the Year of the Rooster, Sending to Yi Yong, Inspector of Iyang
  author: Jeong Mong-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    White clouds rest upon the green mountains,
    yet the wanderer departs from his native land.
    As the year wanes and snow and frost grow heavy,
    why must I journey to such distant places?

    In the station lodge I rise in the middle of night—
    the rooster's cry pierces the darkness: cock-a-doodle-doo.
    At dawn I set forth upon the road ahead,
    and with it rises a sorrow that weighs upon my spirit.

    My old friends grow more distant with each passing day;
    when I turn my head to look back,
    tears fill my eyes like a handful of water.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem appears to be written during Jeong Mong-ju's travels as an official, separated from old friends and the comfort of home. The contrast between the serene natural beauty (white clouds, green mountains) and the speaker's inner melancholy creates the central tension of the work.
